Customer Segmentation for Retail: RFM + Channel Behaviour (PCA + KMeans + RFM Scoring)
Business question
How can we group customers into actionable segments to prioritise CRM and campaigns?
Dataset context
The Superstore file is a demo version of what, in a real company, would be a customer-level feature table built in a warehouse (e.g., BigQuery, Snowflake).
Executive Summary
What we found
Using RFM (Recency, Frequency, Monetary value) plus channel behaviour (online vs store share and web engagement), we identified three operational customer segments (k = 3) that are behaviourally distinct and easy to activate in CRM.
Segments at a glance
  • Mature, high-value, digitally engaged segment (value + engagement leaders)
  • Younger, lower-spend, web-led segment (digital-first, lower basket)
  • Low-spend, low-engagement, largely offline segment (lowest activity and value)
RFM value gradient (strong separation)
  • Best customers: avg spend 1,281 | 28.7 purchases | Recency 21 days
  • Loyal: avg spend 976 | 24.9 purchases | Recency 49 days
  • At risk / lost: avg spend 44 | 11.7 purchases | Recency 82 days
Activation-ready target lists
  • Best customers (295): VIP/exclusivity, early access, premium service
  • Loyal (723): points/benefits, cross-sell journeys, value protection
  • At risk / lost (182): time-boxed win-back offers, browse/basket triggers, re-engagement
How to operationalise
Re-run monthly or quarterly to track segment migration (e.g., Loyal Best) and measure whether campaigns are moving customers up the value ladder.

Conceptually, creating the following features (RFM + Channels) does two things:

  1. Simplify: they condense many raw columns into a few business-compelling metrics.
  2. Focus: they force clusters to form around concepts that interest us (value, channel, product mix), not around noise.

Features created:

Monetary (M): - "Total_Spending" = "MntWines", "MntFruits", "MntMeatProducts", "MntFishProducts", "MntSweetProducts", and "MntGoldProds".

Frequency (F): - "Total_Purchases" = "NumDealsPurchases", "NumWebPurchases", "NumCatalogPurchases", "NumStorePurchases", and "NumWebVisitsMonth".

Recency (R): It is already in the dataset.

Channel mix: - "Online_Purchases" = "NumWebPurchases" +"NumCatalogPurchases" - "Store_Purchases" = "NumStorePurchases"

Dimensionality Reduction (PCA)
Why PCA
Behavioural CRM features are correlated. PCA compresses redundancy into a small number of components, which tends to produce more stable clusters.
Principal Component Analysis
Insight Summary

Insight:
PCA reduced 12 dimensions into 3 components capturing 60.3% of total variance.

Evidence:
PC1: 33.8% variance (cumulative: 33.8%)
PC2: 15.0% variance (cumulative: 48.8%)
PC3: 11.5% variance (cumulative: 60.3%)

Key Component Drivers:
PC1: Total_Spending, Catalogue_Share, Total_Purchases
PC2: Online_Share, Store_Share, NumWebVisitsMonth
PC3: Teenhome, Age, Customer_Tenure

Interpretation:
Components capture limited variance. Data may be highly complex or noisy. PCA may not be the optimal dimensionality reduction technique.

Recommended Action:
Use PCs for customer segmentation, lookalike modelling, or reducing noisy campaign features.

Risk & Caveats:
PCA components are linear combinations and may be harder to interpret. Always validate downstream model performance after dimensionality reduction.

Interpret results considering creative fatigue, audience overlap, frequency capping and campaign pacing.

Mathematical Insight
PC = wX + wX + + w_pX_p
Meaning: PCA compresses many correlated variables into a smaller set of components that still capture most variation.
KMeans Segmentation (on PCA space)
What this does
We group customers with similar behaviour into a small number of segments. Clustering is run on PCA components (PC1PC3) rather than raw features to improve stability.

Implication of segment size
Cluster size translates directly into commercial leverage. A large mid-value segment is typically the primary target for scalable uplift, the smaller high-value segment should be protected through retention and service strategy, and the low-engagement segment is best managed with efficient win-back tactics and channel migration.

Target lists (ready for CRM activation)
What this enables
We can generate CRM audiences directly from the segmentation output (e.g., VIP retention, win-back, growth nudges) while keeping the full customer table intact.
Audience sizes
VIP (Best + Loyal): 1,036 | Growth (Promising + Needs attention): 1,010 | Win-back (At risk / lost): 194
Campaign response by segment (bridge to Predictive)
How to operationalise
Operational workflow (CRM-ready)
  • Build/refresh the customer feature table in the warehouse (RFM + channel mix + engagement).
  • Re-run monthly or quarterly to refresh PCA components and KMeans centroids.
  • Assign customers to segments (PCA transform nearest centroid) and export audiences.
  • Track segment migration and campaign lift to measure ROI.
Assumptions & limitations
Guardrails for interpretation
  • Cluster IDs (0/1/2) are arbitrary and can swap; names should be assigned using the profile table.
  • PCA loadings and RFM cut-offs are dataset-specific; validate when re-training on new periods/businesses.
  • Silhouette can be moderate in behavioural CRM data; success is judged by profile separation and activation lift.
  • This is a demo dataset; in production, features should be refreshed from the warehouse on a schedule.
Decision Tree Explaining RFM Segments
Purpose
This tree is used for explainability: it summarises the RFM segment logic using simple, business-readable rules. It is not intended as a production classifier.

| | | |--- class: Loyal

How to read this tree. The decision tree translates RFM segmentation into a small set of business rules based on Total_Spending, Recency and Total_Purchases:

  • Best customers typically have very high cumulative spend (above ~680) and very recent purchases (Recency 40 days).*
  • Loyal customers also spend heavily (above ~230) and buy relatively recently, but with slightly lower spend than the top tier.
  • Promising customers sit in the middle: moderate to high spend with mixed recency, showing potential to grow into Loyal/Best with the right nudges.
  • Needs attention are lower-spend customers who are still active enough to recover, but require engagement before they drift away.
  • At risk / lost have low spend, few purchases and long recency classic win-back or sunset-programme candidates.

These thresholds can be implemented directly in CRM or marketing automation tools to create VIP, loyalty, nurture and win-back audiences without exposing the underlying model.

*Thresholds (e.g. ~680, ~40 days) are dataset-specific and should be recalibrated when the model is re-trained.
